    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-12-27T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-12-27T06:00:00-05:00" n="58"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d58">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.51W89 U.S.S.R./19: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Marriner</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-12-27T11:00:00+00:00"
                            >December 27, 1933—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 1:20 p.m.<note n="50" xml:id="d58fn50">Telegram in two
                            sections.</note>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>578. For the Acting Secretary and Assistant Secretary <persName corresp="#p_MRW1"
                        >Moore</persName> only from <persName corresp="#p_BWC1">Bullitt</persName>.
                    Soviet Commercial Attaché, Paris, handed me last night list obligations in
                    reichsmarks of the S.S.S.R.<note n="51" xml:id="d58fn51">Soyuz
                        SotsiaUsticheskikh Sovietskikh Respublik.</note> falling due in the year <pb
                        facs="0161" n="55" xml:id="pg_55"/> 1934. He did not give me list of
                    obligations in dollars falling due in Germany for the same period but promised
                    to telegraph to Berlin at once for it. To cable this list in confidential code
                    is impossible without breaking the code since the Soviet Government has the list
                    and <persName>Marriner</persName> and I have agreed that the best method of
                    transmission is the following:</p>
                <p>[Here follows instruction as to method of transmitting the information to the
                        Department.<note n="52" xml:id="d58fn52">The information was duly sent in
                        telegram No. 579, December 28, 11 a.m. (800.51W89 U.S.S.R./20).</note>]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <list>
                            <item>[<persName corresp="#p_BWC1">Bullitt</persName>]</item>
                            <item>
                                <persName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Marriner</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
